We don't high five each other after wins, or throw huge rallies, or hold our football players up on a pedestal, and we don't have a nice big stadium. We have a field with the smallest side lines in the state of California and our weight room is tiny and can barely hold 2 different teams at once. text: Read the book which does a good job of presenting the character of this schools football program through a telling of the actual events. It's not about talent.  As a high school football coach that coached in the bay area I can tell you that DLS does it like no other school in the country IMO. it's a very special place where the players are extraordinarily committed and accountable to each other. I  hope the director gets that right.   It looks like they are taking some liberties with the sequence of events. LB Poly game appears to come at the end in the film but in reality that game happened before the loss to Bellview and is a win in the streak not after. FYI that LB Poly team had 22 players go on to play D1 football.

text: This movie will be decent. Yes, it is high school football but if you want to really know why the DLS Football team is successful you should read, "When the Game Stands Tall". That will give you a complete understanding of why Coach Lad, Edison and the assistants have been successful for so long. It's a process. Neighboring schools, Clayton Valley Charter, don't cut. They carry 100 kids on the Freshmen team. They get no play time and 'wear a jersey' to say they are on the football team. In the end, it is just a game but the brotherhood, commitment, promises and dedication (year round) and discipline to each other results in one of the most storied High School football teams in our nations history. It's not about a long standing streak of wins, it's about becoming a young man through hard work and sacrifice.

text: While it is a great achievement to have a huge winning streak like this it's stupid to assume you will never lose a game. I mean come on, they lose a game and suddenly the world falls apart? Parents beat their kids, the coach has a heart-attack, and people get shot because of it! Outside that town no one gives a crap about a high school football team losing a game. It'll pop up in the paper and people will go "Oh that team lost a game? Too bad but it happens....Oh look dish soap is on sale tomorrow". This trailer makes this football team look like their loss ended world peace.  For the next film we will focus on a high school football team with the largest losing streak and they finally win a game. This event causes an alien invasion of the United States and the return of Shia LaBeouf's career.  EDIT: The trailer doesn't do a good job of conveying when events happened chronologically. The coach's heart-attack and the shooting happen before De La Salle lost the game and yet the trailer makes it look like the events happened after the fact.

text: Football is never about winning nor that it ever has been, now I've played football in middle school and it actually can be fun when I've practiced with my team but they weren't always suppose to fun though and my coach wouldn't risk putting me on the field against any opponent we've played against because he didn't want me to get hurt. He's only done it twice and that's about it, but the coolest experience I ever had practicing. I would believe their were four cones and I think it's called open field tackle, so If I can remember correctly I tackled a kid low around his stomach and I was able to get his feet off the turf grass so landed on his back on the grass. Anyway back to the movie, the 151 win steak is pretty incredible without a doubt. Though it wasn't all about that, it was the team for they their beliefs were and what they stand for as a brotherhood that is almost like a family to be able to help each other out not only on the field but off the field as well is what this movie stood out interpreted like that. It was about their head teaching and helping those young man a direction where it would take them, so I thought in my opinion it was such a good movie that's not only one of the best films in 2014 but also about as good as Friday Night Lights.   P.S. Playing in football for the first time in my life was fun though most of the practices were hard and I didn't get as many opportunities playing on the field against our opponents, but that's okay I didn't feel like I was fit in. In my high school years, I've participated in Track & Field from my freshmen year to senior year, and I also join Cross Country in my sophomore year. At least I was able to experience playing for a football team.

text: Here’s a great idea. You know how every sports movie ever made is about the pathetic underdog team that never wins any games, then at the end of the movie they end up beating the undefeated douchebag team? What if we subverted that and make the undefeated team the protagonist and have the audience try to sympathize with them when they act like cry bandies when they lose one game out of over 100 games. Then have the team not learn any humiliation, and end the movie with them winning again and continuing to act like egotistical assholes. Thus teaching the audience that if you don’t win all the time, your life will be ruined and all your loved ones will die.
